Data Lab makes extensive use of International Virtual Observatory Alliance (IVOA; http://www.ivoa.net/ ) protocols and implementations developed elsewhere in its services.

In particular, Data Lab uses: Table Access Protocol (TAP), based on the implementation by CADC Simple Image Access (SIA) protocol VOSpace based on the implementation by CADC (https://www.canfar.net/en/docs/storage/ ) Universal Worker Service (UWS) standard DALServer based on the implementation by NRAO (https://github.com/TomMcGlynn/usvirtualobservatory/tree/ master/usvao/prototype/dalserver ) PyVO Python library ( https://pyvo.readthedocs.io/en/latest/ ) Data Lab also uses several Open Source software projects as part of its services, including: PostgreSQL ( https://www.postgresql.org ) as its large catalog database solution Q3C (Koposov & Bartunov, 2019) for spatial indexing, cone searches, and cross-matching 7

Project Jupyter ( https://jupyter.org ) as its analysis platform AstroPy (Astropy Collaboration et al., 2013; Price-Whelan et al., 2018) and afﬁliated packages Data Lab is actively developing the use of Docker ( https://www.docker.com ) Containers and Container orchestration through Kubernetes ( https://kubernetes.io ) for service management and deployment.
As part of its technology development roadmap, Data Lab aims to ensure future compatibility with the LSST Science Platform ( https://ldm-542.lsst.io ).
